<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIRE BURNS 200 ACRES NEAR LEBEC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A disabled car that caught fire beside the Golden State Freeway just north of 
the Los Angeles County line set off a brush fire Thursday that leaped the 
eight-lane roadway and burned across steep hillsides near Los Padres National 
Forest, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Within three hours of starting at 1:45 p.m., the flames had destroyed nearly 
200 acres in the Tejon Pass as nearly 500 firefighters fought the blaze, said 
Deputy Chief Steve Gage of the Kern County Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
 Firefighters from Kern, Ventura, Los Angeles, Riverside and San Bernardino 
counties were aided by helicopters and air tankers, Gage said. The fire was 
almost directly across from Fort Tejon State Park, about half a mile north of 
the town of Lebec, Gage said. 
</P>
<P>
 The blaze came close to a school, but had damaged no structures by late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Using bulldozers and hand crews, firefighters dug a fire line in an effort to 
contain the fire to about 700 acres, Gage said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We hope to have it contained by midnight," he said. "We just hope the fire 
line holds." 
</P>
