<P>
COUNTY SCHOOL PROGRAM CITED AS U.S. MODEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Los Angeles County program has been cited as a national model for decreasing 
violence in schools. The county Office of Education's Teacher Expectation and 
Student Achievement program, begun in 1971, was recently recommended by the New 
York State Board of Regents as a model training program to help teachers 
promote school safety. The program concentrates on helping teachers become more 
aware of the needs of their students, addressing such issues as teacher bias 
and ethnic diversity. 
