April, illegally received or passed on inside information this spring, the 
paper said in today's editions.During the time in question, Angell was warning 
clients that the Fed was likely to raise interest rates significantly, the 
newspaper said. Angell said there was nothing to investigate. The inquiry 
follows an internal Fed investigation that found no evidence of wrongdoing. 
